# Network Inventory

A practical overview of the main Docker and service network boundaries used across Homelab Steampunk.

> Primary application network: `steampunknet`  
> Dedicated stack networks: `nextcloud-aio`, `seafile-net`  
> LAN-facing services: `br0`  
> Host-integrated services: `host`

---

# At a Glance

| Network | Primary Role | Notes |
|:--|:--|:--|
| `steampunknet` | Main application network | Primary network for most containers |
| `nextcloud-aio` | Dedicated Nextcloud stack network | Isolates the AIO service family |
| `seafile-net` | Dedicated Seafile network | Keeps Seafile and its DB grouped |
| `br0` | LAN-facing infrastructure | Used for services that benefit from direct LAN presence |
| `host` | Host-integrated services | Used when direct host visibility or integration is needed |
| `bridge` | Default Docker bridge | Used selectively for a smaller number of services |

---

# Core Network Roles

| Network | Role | Why It Exists |
|:--|:--|:--|
| `steampunknet` | Main application backbone | Keeps most application containers in a shared custom network instead of a flat default layout |
| `nextcloud-aio` | Stack-specific grouping | Keeps Nextcloud AIO components logically grouped and more isolated |
| `seafile-net` | Service-specific grouping | Creates a cleaner network boundary for Seafile and its backend |
| `br0` | Local network service presence | Supports services that belong more naturally on the LAN |
| `host` | Direct host integration | Supports services that need tighter host-level visibility or behavior |
| `bridge` | Limited default use | Retained where the default Docker bridge is sufficient |

